         3. The A6 philosophy

         The A6 philosophy is simple: to produce a cross-assembler that
         assembles 6502 code efficiently and quickly, while retaining
         the syntax from the familiar "Laser Genius" assembler for the
         Commodore 64, as well as grafting in some of the command set
         from "Turbo Assembler".

         Many Turbo Assembler users have said to me that they won't use
         A6 because it doesn't use the Turbo Assembler syntax.
         Actually, the original Turbo is mainly a subset of the Genius
         syntax, and I suspect that both emulate some earlier, more
         obscure assembler.  Generally, both Genius and Turbo programms
         should (eventually) feel right at home with A6, and source
         codes written for either should be fairly portable to A6.  A
         quick nod will be made towards the command sets of AS65 and
         C64ASM, in order to make those users more comfortable as well.

         However, with the source code for A6 now freely available, it
         is possible for the user to modify the command set to suit
         themselves.  It is possible, in fact, that one day, I will
         separate the grammar from the assembler to the extent that it
         is changeable on the fly.  Which would be nice.





































