         4. Compiling and installing A6

         4.1 Compiling A6

         First of all, you will need to configure the source code for
         your platform.  There are three scripts you can run, depending
         on the platform that you are using.

         On Amiga DOS, type
             execute config.ami

         On MS-DOS, type
             config.bat

         On Unix, type
            chmod 755 config
            ./config

         The configuration script will then churn away and attempt to
         find the preferred compiler for your system, and then make the
         files "makefile" and "conf.h".  The configuration script will
         then print out the necessary steps to finish compiling A6.

         The final stage is to test the assembler;  this will be done by
         a program called "compare".  If compare reports any errors,
         please email the file "compare.txt" to
         simon@powerfield.demon.co.uk.

         If you need to make alterations to conf.h and makefile for
         another compiler, please e-mail them to
         simon@powerfield.demon.co.uk so that I can include the
         configuration details into the configuration scripts.


         4.1.1 Currently supported Amiga C compilers

         4.1.1.1 Lattice C

         A6 is written primarily with Lattice C under OS3.  There are no
         known problems with the Amiga configuration under Lattice C 5,
         although Lattice is missing several important defines from the
         latest ANSI standard.

         4.1.1.2 SAS C

         This is the latest version (that I know of) of the Lattice
         series of compilers.  As far as I am aware, there should be no
         problems compiling it with the script provided in config.ami.
         However, this has not been tested; if changes are required to
         the makefile and conf.h, please inform me.


         4.1.2 Currently supported MS-DOS compilers

         4.1.2.1 Borland C





