         I have successfully compiled A6 using a hand-written makefile,
         using Borland C 4.  Support for this compiler will follow in
         the next release.

         4.1.2.2 DJGPP (GNU C)

         DJGPP is the compiler under which the project began, and is
         therefore the preferred compiler for DOS.  I have set the
         makefile for a 386 or better.  DJGPP requires DPMI memory, and
         will not therefore compile on anything less than a 386.


         4.1.3 Currently supported Unix compilers

         4.1.3.1 GNU C

         The makefile for GNU C on Unix is written using new style
         rules, '%.o %.c', rather than '.c.o'.  If the makefile throws
         an error, you need to change this line in the makefile.


         4.2 Installing A6

         If you have compiled A6, you can install it using the target
         "install". by typing

             make install

         Under Unix systems, the binary will live in the directory
         /usr/local/bin.  Amiga makefiles copy the result into c:, where
         as DOS makefiles copy the result into c:\utils, which is where
         the result lives on my system.  For DOS installations, you may
         wish to alter this path or copy it directly.

         If you have downloaded a binary distribution, simply extract
         the zip, lzh or .tar.gz file into a directory and copy the
         binary into the directory of your choice.


         4.3 Important notice for Amiga users

         Amiga hard drive handling appears to be rather slow.  As A6 is
         quite heavy on disk usage, you might want to add another 20 or
         40 buffers to dh0:

             addbuffers dh0: 25

         At some point, I intend to try and take some load off the disk
         usage if I can.  At the moment, however, stability  and
         functionality are the prime concerns.


