         5. Using A6

         A6 is a command-line assembler.  You will need a text editor to
         edit source files, and some way of executing the results.

         The general command line takes this format:

             a6 [switches] filename

         The switches have the following meaning:

         -d
              this switch makes the dot in front of assembler directives
              optional.  Thus, ".byte" could be used as "byte", without
              the leading dot.  This option is intended to help
              compatability with the AS65 assembler.

         -f<format>
              sets the output file format:
                -fb   Binary, assembled bytes written direct to output
                -fp   PRG file (Commodore binary file)
                -f0   P00 file (used by the PC64 emulator)

         -l
              generate listing (to standard output) on pass 2.

         -o<filename>
              set output filename.

              If no output filename is specified, it defaults to the
              name of the source file, with the appropriate extension.

         -s<0|1|2>
              restrict assembler syntax.  -s2 is the default.
                -s0   Laser Genius directives only
                -s1   Laser Genius and other assembler directives
                -s2   All directives, including A6 extensions

         -t
              list symbol table after assembly.

         Switches cannot be combined:  thus, '-fps0' is not equivalent
         to '-fp -s0'.


         5.1 Input and output file formats

         File format     Include    Output   Notes
         raw             .incbin    -fb      This is the default file
         format
         PRG file        .incprg    -fp
         P00 file        .incp00    -f0      Used by PC64 emulator








