         7. Source file format

         In A6, each line consists of up to three fields.  Before the
         fields are generated, comments are stripped from the line.
         Comments always begin with the semi-colon character,  ';'.

         The possible line combinations are as follows:
             label
             label    = value
             label    opcode      expression
                      opcode      expression
             label    directive   [expression]
                      directive   [expression]

         Labels always begin in the first column of the line.  Opcodes
         always begin after some whitespace.  This was done as an
         optimisation, and generally does not, in my experience, tend to
         conflict with most programmers' indenting habits.


         7.1 Labels

         Labels can begin with any alphabetic character, or an
         underscore.  After that, labels can then consist of any
         alphanumeric character, underscore, dollar sign or dot.

         To access a global label within a local block, or to define a
         global label within a local block, precede it with an
         exclamation mark.  Thus, within a local section:
             label1
         and
             !label1
         do not refer to the same address.  A6 supports up to 32000
         local sections, which should be more than enough for most
         practical projects.

         The label "*" is reserved, and always refers to the current
         assembly position.

         You can enter a new namespace by using '.local' to enter the
         namespace, and '.endloc' to exit it.


         7.2 Opcodes

         Opcodes are case sensitive.  The following opcodes are
         supported:

             aax*   adc    alr*   amb*   and    asl    aso*   axh*
             axs*   bcc    bcs    beq    bit    bmi    bne    bpl
             brk    bvc    bvs    clc    cld    cli    clv    cmp
             cpx    cpy    cra*   dcm*   dec    dex    dey    eor
             hxm*   hym*   inc    ins    inx    iny    jmp    jsr
             las*   lax*   lda    ldx    ldy    lse*   lsr    nop
             npo*   oax*   ora    pha    php    pla    plp    rla*
             rol    ror    rra*   rti    rts    sax*   sbc    sec
             sed    sei    skb*   skw*   sta    stx    sty    sub*
             tax    tay    tsx    txa    txs    tya    xma*


         Page 11                                                17/01/98


         A6 0.4.3 documentation          Copyright A6 Development Team, 1998



         Opcodes that are marked with a star are undocumented, and can
         only be used when undocumented opcodes are switched on.  Please
         see section 8.9 for details of switching undocumented opcodes
         on.

         Opcodes are case-sensitive, thus BRK is not recognised as an
         opcode.


         7.3 Expressions

         Expressions are evaluated in a strict left-to-right order.
         Mathematical precedence is ignored.  Although this is somewhat
         non-intuitive behaviour, it is consistent with Genius, and
         allows the code to be easily read.  The following arithmetic
         expressions are supported:

             +                addition
             -                subtraction
             *                multiplication
             /                division

             ^ or |           bitwise inclusive-OR
             ^^ or ||         logical inclusive-OR (returns 0 or 1)
             &                bitwise AND
             &&               logical AND (returns 0 or 1)
             ?                bitwise EOR
             ??               logical EOR (returns 0 or 1)

             label1           label
             [label1]         is label defined? (returns 0 or 1)
             12345            denary (base 10) number
             $3039            hexadecimal (base 16) number
             @30071           octal number
             %1100000111001   binary number
             *                current assembly position

         Values can be prefixed with '-' to take the two's complement
         value.

         Expressions can be prefixed with '<' or '>'.  '<' allows the
         expression to return the lower 8 bits of the expression;  '>'
         allows the expression to return the upper 8 bits of the
         expression.  These are equivalent, respectively, to suffixing
         the expressions with '&255' and '/256'.

         Note: overflows and underflows in arithmetic are not detected,
         and do not cause either errors of warnings.  However, division
         by zero does cause a non-fatal error.










