         8. Assembler directives

         Assemblers directives under A6 divide into three groups:
         Genius directives, Turbo Assembler directives, and A6
         extensions.  In this list, Turbo Assembler syntax (-s1) is
         marked with a star (*), and A6 extensions (-s2) are marked with
         two (**).

         You can specify that you want to drop the dot from the
         beginning of directives by adding the switch "-d" to the
         command line.


         8.1 .add** <value>, .eor* <value>

         These directives encode the output stream in whatever manner
         you desire.  Eor is part of the extended Turbo Assembler
         specification, and Add I have added for A6.

         Add is guaranteed to be performed _before_ Eor, thus the
         fragment

                     ldx #$0c
           lp1       lda encoded,x
                     eor #$40
                     sec
                     sbc #$20
                     sta $0400,x
                     lda #$01
                     sta $d800,x
                     dex
                     bpl lp1
                     rts

                     .eor $40
                     .add $20
           encoded   .tscrl "Hello, world!"

         Would print "Hello, World!" on the screen.  (This example is
         unashamedly CBM64 centric.  Sorry!)


         8.2 .align** <expression>

         Aligns the object code to a position;  especially important for
         time-intensive loops, where you don't need the cross-page
         timing penalties.  The expression should evaluate to a power of
         two, such as 4, 8, 16 or 256;  however, any expression is
         accepted, zero being automatically converted to 256.


         8.3 .block <expression>, .pad <expression>

         These two directives are included for Genius compatability.
         They both do the same thing, which is to pad the output stream
         with the required number of NOP codes ($EA).




         Page 13                                                17/01/98


         A6 0.4.3 documentation          Copyright A6 Development Team, 1998


         Note that this is _slightly_ different from the Genius syntax,
         because in Genius .block skips memory;  when I get round to
         supporting hex output formats, I'll make it conform to the
         Genius specification.

         Another point is that .block is used in some versions of Turbo
         Assembler for what I've called .local (an A6 extension).  This
         is also used by Thomas Lehmann's AS65 assembler on the Amiga.
         It's unfortunate, but to change .block would be to make A6
         break the Genius syntax.


         8.4 .byte <list>

         Shorthand: .byt

         This directive parses a comma-separated list of values and
         writes the output to the output file.

         Labels and characters are welcome in the output stream, and the
         following would be quite legal:

                     .byte "The zero page value is ",zz01,0

         provided the value of zz01 was 8-bit (i.e. did not exceed
         0xFF).

         If values do exceed 8-bits, a non-fatal error will be
         generated.  Text is interpreted according to the current
         character set, see section 8.5.


         8.5 .cset** <csetname>

         This directive sets the current output stream character set.
         The default is PET ASCII, but can also be PC ASCII, upper-case
         screen characters or lower-case screen characters.  Valid
         arguments for this opcode are as follows:

           ascii       PC ascii
           pet         PET ASCII
           scrl        lower-case screen characters
           scru        upper-case screen characters


         8.6 .echo** <string>

         Just your average echo;  copies the string given directly to
         the output.  At some time, I might change that so that it can
         print variables and so on, but for now, it's just an echo.


         8.7 .incbin** <filename>, .incprg** <filename>, .incp00**
         <filename>

         These directives specify that the required file is to be
         included directly in the output stream.  The file is opened,



         Page 14                                                17/01/98


         A6 0.4.3 documentation          Copyright A6 Development Team, 1998


         and its contents copied to the output stream at the current
         assembly position.

         .incbin assumes that the file is a straight binary file, such
         as A6 produces with no arguments (aka a Commodore SEQ file).

         .incprg assumes that the file is a Commodore PRG file, which
         contains the load address in the first two bytes.  The load
         address is ignored.

         .incp00 reads the file from a PC64 file image.  The header
         details and file load address are ignored.


         8.8 .include** <filename>

         Shorthand: .inc

         This directive specifies that the required file is to be
         processed as though it were part of the current file.  The file
         is opened, read in, and then closed once the file finishes.
         Control returns to the file that opened it.

         You can nest .include directives up to a limit of 32.  There
         are a maximum of 64 files allowed per project, which on the
         CBM64 tends asymptotically towards about 1,024 bytes of object
         code per file.


         8.9 .local**, .endloc**

         .local begins a local block, and .endloc leaves the block.
         Within a local block, labels with the same name as global
         labels can be defined and used as though they were global
         labels.  When .endloc is encountered, A6 leaves the block and
         returns, either to the local block outside the current local
         block (they can be nested up to 32 blocks deep), or to the
         global structure.  Here is an example:

             label1 = 4
                    .local
             label1 = 5
                    .byte label1
                    .endloc
                    .byte label1

         This piece of code produces the bytes $05 $04 in the object
         code.

         Please see section 7.1 for further details.


         8.10 .org <expression>

         You can set the output position for your code using this
         directive.  However, ".org" can be used only _once_ per
         assembly stream, and if you try to use it again, it throws an



         Page 15                                                17/01/98


         A6 0.4.3 documentation          Copyright A6 Development Team, 1998


         error.  If you want to re-define the output position, use `*='
         or .block or .pad (see section 8.2)


         8.11 .tasc**, .text*, .tpet**, .tscrl**, .tscru**, .txt**

         These six directives are similar to .byte, but only support
         text directives.  Labels, numeric expressions and other values
         are not permitted in text lines.

         .text and .txt support the current global characterset, as
         defined by .cset.  The others are designed to be used locally,
         where another character set is temporarily required:

           .tasc     PC ascii
           .tpet     PET ascii
           .tscrl    Lower-case screen characters
           .tscru    Upper-case screen characters


         8.12 .undoc**, .noundoc**

         Enable and disable undocumented opcodes.  These work, although
         they will be replaced later by a method of loadable CPU tables.


         8.13 .ver <version>

         This directive came in with version 0.4.3, and is compared to
         an internal number that indicates the version number.  The
         current version is $0403, and you can use this number to define
         that your source code requires A6 v0.4.3 or better.

         A6 assumes that the next minor version is incompatible enough
         to be worthy of an upgrade;  therefore, .ver $0500 will always
         cause your source code to fail.


         8.14 .word <expression>

         This directive parses a comma-separated list of 16-bit values
         and writes the output to the output file, in low/high format
         (low byte first).

         Labels are welcome in the output stream, and the following
         would be quite legal:

                     .word $1234,ad01,0

         If values do exceed 16-bits, a non-fatal error will be
         generated.









